00:16:48,801 --> 00:16:49,802
You know each other?

249
00:16:49,886 --> 00:16:51,763
I see my brother
nailed you, eh?

250
00:16:51,804 --> 00:16:54,474
Your brother? Yeah,
believe it or not.

251
00:16:54,515 --> 00:16:57,143
If he wouldn't have pulled that old
crotch trick, he never would have won.

252
00:16:57,185 --> 00:16:58,311
That's his best move.

253
00:16:58,394 --> 00:17:00,021
Runs in the family.

254
00:17:00,104 --> 00:17:01,856
Well, it worked.

255
00:17:01,939 --> 00:17:02,982
What are we drinkin'?

256
00:17:03,024 --> 00:17:05,151
Champagne of
the working classes.

257
00:17:05,651 --> 00:17:07,653
Beer. And you
owe me a couple.

258
00:17:07,695 --> 00:17:09,113
That's right.
Comin' up.

259
00:17:09,155 --> 00:17:11,657
Two beers. So, you
work at the park, huh?

260
00:17:11,699 --> 00:17:13,326
Mmm-hmm.
I'm a water skier.

261
00:17:13,409 --> 00:17:14,410
Oh.

262
00:17:14,911 --> 00:17:17,830
(LAUGHING)
Your brother's cute.

263
00:17:17,872 --> 00:17:22,668
Yeah. Him and Kathryn have, uh,
been together for a year and a half.

264
00:17:23,419 --> 00:17:24,921
How about you?

265
00:17:26,005 --> 00:17:27,882
Desperately unattached.

266
00:17:28,674 --> 00:17:31,260
Lonely, confused.

267
00:17:32,678 --> 00:17:36,766
Generous and loving to
a fault. It's all in my eyes.

268
00:17:38,601 --> 00:17:40,144
MAN 1: (WHISPERING) Come On.
MAN 2: (WHISPERING) Okay.

269
00:17:40,186 --> 00:17:41,687
We'll cop a lot of
good stuff tonight.

270
00:17:41,896 --> 00:17:43,272
I've got the tanks.

271
00:17:43,439 --> 00:17:44,524
Shh!

272
00:17:44,565 --> 00:17:46,317
Is the van okay here?

273
00:17:46,359 --> 00:17:47,860
Yes, it's okay.

274
00:17:47,944 --> 00:17:51,405
We're off SeaWorld property.
Nobody uses this road.

275
00:17:56,119 --> 00:17:57,245
Shh!

276
00:17:58,371 --> 00:17:59,497
Yeah.

277
00:18:00,206 --> 00:18:01,415
All right.

278
00:18:02,416 --> 00:18:03,501
Yeah.

279
00:18:03,543 --> 00:18:06,629
Climb over the fence, and
take it easy with the raft.

280
00:18:06,712 --> 00:18:08,005
(CLATTERING)

281
00:18:08,047 --> 00:18:09,590
Damn it!

282
00:18:11,759 --> 00:18:13,302
You asshole.

283
00:18:13,386 --> 00:18:15,680
Now we gotta drag it all
the way down to the water!

284
00:18:16,430 --> 00:18:17,557
Ready to go?

285
00:18:17,640 --> 00:18:19,809
Okay. Who's payin'?

286
00:18:28,609 --> 00:18:29,652
Ah.

287
00:18:39,245 --> 00:18:40,413
Watch out. Snakes.

288
00:18:40,496 --> 00:18:42,665
Oh, come on.
Don't bullshit me.

289
00:18:42,748 --> 00:18:44,208
Chicken, huh?

290
00:18:53,092 --> 00:18:54,093
(CROAKING)
(MAN GASPS)

291
00:18:54,927 --> 00:18:57,054
All right, steady.

292
00:18:57,680 --> 00:18:59,098
Steady.
Got it.

293
00:19:00,433 --> 00:19:02,059
Okay. Here we go.

294
00:19:02,810 --> 00:19:03,936
Come on, paddle!

295
00:19:04,020 --> 00:19:05,104
I am.

296
00:19:05,771 --> 00:19:07,940
Let's go out to the center.

297
00:19:08,232 --> 00:19:10,443
I sure hope
this is worth it.

298
00:19:16,115 --> 00:19:17,366
(LAUGHING)

299
00:19:17,450 --> 00:19:18,576
(MIKE GROANING)

300
00:19:18,951 --> 00:19:20,494
Hey, Kelly,
is this your car?

301
00:19:20,578 --> 00:19:21,621
Sure is.

302
00:19:22,288 --> 00:19:25,124
Hey. Get off of there!

303
00:19:25,208 --> 00:19:26,959
(GROANING)

304
00:19:27,001 --> 00:19:29,086
You wanna take a walk? Yeah.

305
00:19:29,128 --> 00:19:31,339
Hey, what about
baby brother?

306
00:19:31,923 --> 00:19:33,758
Aww! Aww!

307
00:19:34,133 --> 00:19:36,135
Little baby brother.

308
00:19:36,969 --> 00:19:39,472
Kelly, can you give him a ride
home, or shall I call his mommy?

309
00:19:39,555 --> 00:19:41,974
Nah, if he'll come quietly.

310
00:19:42,058 --> 00:19:43,851
No way. I scream and shout.

311
00:19:43,976 --> 00:19:46,354
Oh, God, it stinks out
here. Let's get away!

312
00:19:46,437 --> 00:19:47,772
See ya.

313
00:19:47,813 --> 00:19:49,565
Hey, let's go swimming.

314
00:19:49,649 --> 00:19:51,067
No, I hate the ocean.

315
00:19:51,150 --> 00:19:54,153
Aww! Hey, I've got
a better idea.

316
00:19:54,237 --> 00:19:55,488
Like lagoons?

317
00:19:55,571 --> 00:19:56,864
Lagoons?

318
00:19:57,990 --> 00:19:59,033
Lagoons.

319
00:19:59,116 --> 00:20:00,243
(LAUGHING)

320
00:20:00,576 --> 00:20:01,661
(ENGINE STARTING)

321
00:20:07,166 --> 00:20:10,711
Oh. How come Sean
doesn't visit more?

322
00:20:10,795 --> 00:20:12,797
He hates the water.
What?

323
00:20:12,838 --> 00:20:18,177
Yeah. Remember that shark attack I
told you about when we were kids in Amity?

324
00:20:19,345 --> 00:20:22,223
Well, that's why he goes
to school in Colorado.

325
00:20:22,306 --> 00:20:25,309
If our parents didn't live on an
island, I don't think he'd ever get wet.

326
00:20:25,351 --> 00:20:27,687
(LAUGHING)
My dad, he's the same way.

327
00:20:31,232 --> 00:20:33,150
God, I love this place.

328
00:20:34,235 --> 00:20:36,737
I hated it when
we first came here.

329
00:20:37,530 --> 00:20:39,198
What's the matter?

330
00:20:41,575 --> 00:20:43,786
Did you get a telephone call?

331
00:20:46,706 --> 00:20:48,040
Venezuela?

332
00:20:50,209 --> 00:20:52,420
Guess I'm gonna have to
start learning Spanish.

333
00:20:52,503 --> 00:20:55,464
(EXHALING) Ooh, baby.
Yeah. Yeah.

334
00:20:56,632 --> 00:20:59,802
That's wonderful.
That's wonderful.

335
00:21:00,845 --> 00:21:02,596
Oh, shit.

336
00:21:03,973 --> 00:21:05,224
Reality.

337
00:21:06,976 --> 00:21:08,227
How long?

338
00:21:09,145 --> 00:21:11,355
Just a short
year and a half.

339
00:21:16,652 --> 00:21:18,946
I'd love you to come,
you know.

340
00:21:19,488 --> 00:21:20,573
Yeah.

341
00:21:23,075 --> 00:21:26,579
But what about the six
months I've got left here

342
00:21:27,163 --> 00:21:30,124
and the job opening up
at the Scripps Institute?

343
00:21:30,207 --> 00:21:33,544
What about that? Huh?

344
00:21:33,586 --> 00:21:37,256
Simple. Just give up
your life and follow me.

345
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:39,258
(LAUGHING)

346
00:21:41,093 --> 00:21:43,596
Oh, I'm happy
for you. I am.

347
00:21:43,637 --> 00:21:44,930
I know you are.

348
00:21:47,099 --> 00:21:48,893
What are we gonna do?

349
00:21:55,941 --> 00:21:57,443
A-ha.
Mm-hmm.

350
00:22:05,868 --> 00:22:07,453
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

351
00:22:17,338 --> 00:22:18,881
(GRUNTING)
(LAUGHING)

352
00:22:21,634 --> 00:22:22,968
(CHUCKLING)

353
00:22:25,638 --> 00:22:27,139
(CHUCKLING)

354
00:22:28,599 --> 00:22:29,809
Come on.

355
00:22:30,434 --> 00:22:32,311
Oh, I don't go in the water.

356
00:22:32,395 --> 00:22:33,646
You don't swim?

357
00:22:34,730 --> 00:22:36,607
Not even with friends?

358
00:22:37,149 --> 00:22:41,779
Oh, uh, I swim.
I just, uh, I... I...

359
00:22:43,531 --> 00:22:45,783
(SIGHING) It's something
that happened when I was a kid.

360
00:22:45,825 --> 00:22:48,244
I just, I don't go in the water.
(LAUGHING AWKWARDLY)

361
00:22:51,330 --> 00:22:53,999
I bet I can overcome
your childhood fears.

362
00:23:02,007 --> 00:23:03,509
I bet you can.

363
00:23:06,303 --> 00:23:07,513
Come on.

364
00:23:09,515 --> 00:23:10,808
My boots!

365
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:13,394
Kick 'em off, cowboy.

366
00:23:21,902 --> 00:23:23,112
Kelly!

367
00:23:23,195 --> 00:23:25,865
Come on in, Sean.
It's fun.

368
00:23:28,784 --> 00:23:30,035
Come on.

369
00:23:32,580 --> 00:23:33,664
Here?

370
00:23:33,706 --> 00:23:35,207
Yeah, okay.

371
00:23:35,291 --> 00:23:37,084
Somewhere down there
is the best coral.

372
00:23:37,168 --> 00:23:40,421
A guy in Miami will give us
$200 for the good stuff.

373
00:23:41,547 --> 00:23:44,091
Put it in the basket.
I'll pull it up.

374
00:23:58,189 --> 00:24:00,357
(KELLY LAUGHING IN DISTANCE)

375
00:24:06,655 --> 00:24:08,407
Come on, hurry, Randy.

376
00:24:22,463 --> 00:24:25,424
KAY: I love this park
at night. It's so deserted.

377
00:24:25,466 --> 00:24:26,884
MIKE: Yeah. So quiet.

378
00:24:26,926 --> 00:24:29,428
Wait a second.
Isn't that Kelly's car?

379
00:24:29,470 --> 00:24:32,097
Stop, stop, stop.
Shh! Wait a second.

380
00:24:33,015 --> 00:24:34,099
Stop.

381
00:24:35,893 --> 00:24:36,936
Shh.

382
00:24:51,617 --> 00:24:52,952
(GIGGLING)

383
00:25:08,467 --> 00:25:10,052
I don't believe it.

384
00:25:10,135 --> 00:25:11,470
She got him in the water.

385
00:25:12,304 --> 00:25:14,807
Never underestimate
the power, huh?

386
00:25:30,197 --> 00:25:34,827
<i>Attention. You, in the water. You
are trespassing on SeaWorld property.</i>

387
00:25:34,868 --> 00:25:38,747
<i>Come out of the water with your
hands raised high above your head.</i>

388
00:25:38,956 --> 00:25:41,709
I'm okay.
My brother works here.

389
00:25:41,792 --> 00:25:44,503
Uh, I'm Kelly Ann Bukowski,
from the ski team.

390
00:25:45,879 --> 00:25:47,840
<i>You turkeys have any ID?</i>

391
00:25:49,174 --> 00:25:50,676
Wait a minute.

392
00:25:51,010 --> 00:25:53,095
Mike? Kay?
Brother?

393
00:25:53,512 --> 00:25:55,389
<i>Mr. Bullhorn sees all,
knows all!</i>

394
00:25:55,472 --> 00:25:57,266
<i>Dead is what you are!</i>

395
00:25:58,851 --> 00:26:00,644
<i>You keep your hands
to yourself, young m...</i>

396
00:26:00,686 --> 00:26:02,354
(KELLY SCREECHING)

397
00:26:02,688 --> 00:26:04,064
Here, take this.

398
00:26:04,148 --> 00:26:05,482
MIKE: Yell for mother!

399
00:26:08,319 --> 00:26:09,903
(MIKE AND SEAN SHOUTING
IN THE DISTANCE)

400
00:26:10,613 --> 00:26:12,698
Finish up down there,
damn it!

401
00:26:12,781 --> 00:26:14,658
Come on, Randy.
We gotta get out of here!

402
00:26:14,700 --> 00:26:16,785
(MUFFLED THUD)
Now what?

403
00:26:21,332 --> 00:26:22,374
Ow!

404
00:26:33,218 --> 00:26:34,637
(SHOUTING)

405
00:26:35,512 --> 00:26:36,889
KELLY: Mike!

406
00:26:38,932 --> 00:26:40,434
(GIRLS SCREECHING)

407
00:26:41,393 --> 00:26:43,562
(GIRLS YELLING)

408
00:26:47,941 --> 00:26:49,443
KAY: You cheater!
(SCREAMING)

409
00:26:55,157 --> 00:26:57,493
SEAN: That's what
you are! Dead!

410
00:27:02,539 --> 00:27:04,917
Some guys can sleep in
in the morning.

411
00:27:04,958 --> 00:27:08,212
Some of us have to be at
work early. Good morning.

412
00:27:08,253 --> 00:27:12,174
Some of us don't have to baby-sit
a park full of slugs and fishes either.

413
00:27:12,257 --> 00:27:15,594
Yes, we just live like slugs and
fishes. Good morning, Maggie.

414
00:27:15,678 --> 00:27:18,847
The dog does not eat on
the counter. (GROANING)

415
00:27:20,265 --> 00:27:22,601
I put your wet clothes
in the dryer, sweetie.

416
00:27:22,685 --> 00:27:25,187
Thanks.
Mmm. What are we eating?

417
00:27:25,896 --> 00:27:28,107
Mmm. Thank you.

418
00:27:30,275 --> 00:27:32,444
Hey, is this my beeper
or your beeper?

419
00:27:32,528 --> 00:27:33,862
I don't know.
I'll use this beeper.

420
00:27:33,946 --> 00:27:35,781
Use that beeper.

421
00:27:35,864 --> 00:27:36,865
Talk to you later.

422
00:27:36,949 --> 00:27:38,617
I'll have my beeper
beep your beeper.

423
00:27:38,659 --> 00:27:40,661
I'll have my beeper
beep your beeper back.

424
00:27:41,912 --> 00:27:43,706
Bye.
See you later.

425
00:27:46,583 --> 00:27:47,626
Aye.

426
00:27:48,544 --> 00:27:49,545
Coffee?

427
00:27:50,379 --> 00:27:53,465
Just throw it in my eyes,
it'll work faster.

428
00:27:53,549 --> 00:27:55,384
Yeah, well that's what happens
when you stay up all night

429
00:27:55,467 --> 00:27:57,594
workin' out your
childhood phobias.

430
00:27:57,636 --> 00:27:59,763
That's right. Make fun
of your baby brother.

431
00:27:59,805 --> 00:28:03,225
But I was this close to
doing it in the water last night,

432
00:28:03,308 --> 00:28:05,018
and that's a first.

433
00:28:05,894 --> 00:28:07,146
This close, huh?
Shut up!

434
00:28:07,354 --> 00:28:08,605
(LAUGHING)

435
00:28:10,691 --> 00:28:12,943
Oh, I'm sorry. I didn't
know it was therapy.

436
00:28:13,318 --> 00:28:15,112
Just admit it.
You messed me up.

437
00:28:15,696 --> 00:28:17,990
I admit it.
I messed you up.

438
00:28:19,491 --> 00:28:21,702
Is everything all right
between you and Kathryn?

439
00:28:21,785 --> 00:28:22,828
(PHONE RINGING)

440
00:28:22,911 --> 00:28:23,996
Hello?

441
00:28:24,872 --> 00:28:26,123
Yes, sir.

442
00:28:29,668 --> 00:28:32,171
Calvin, I had my crew
on that yesterday.

443
00:28:33,297 --> 00:28:35,758
Well, I know. I don't
want that to happen either.

444
00:28:36,300 --> 00:28:38,302
(SIGHING) Tomorrow.

445
00:28:39,845 --> 00:28:42,639
Okay, Okay. Calvin,
I'll be right there.

446
00:28:42,681 --> 00:28:43,932
The boss, right?

447
00:28:44,850 --> 00:28:45,893
I gotta go to work.

448
00:28:49,229 --> 00:28:52,024
Yeah, can't do better
than that! Really.

449
00:28:52,649 --> 00:28:54,026
(SQUEAKING)

450
00:28:55,694 --> 00:28:57,696
Yeah. Yeah!

451
00:28:57,905 --> 00:29:00,199
Who's a good girl?
That's my baby.

452
00:29:00,449 --> 00:29:01,867
DAN: Kay?

453
00:29:03,202 --> 00:29:05,120
KAY: How are
Cindy and Sandy?

454
00:29:05,370 --> 00:29:07,873
Well, Cindy's okay,
but Sandy's still nervous.

455
00:29:10,793 --> 00:29:13,545
KAY: Don't quit, Danny.
He can go higher.

456
00:29:17,716 --> 00:29:19,051
That's it!

457
00:29:22,554 --> 00:29:24,264
Okay, girls.
There are my girls.

458
00:29:24,348 --> 00:29:27,935
Thank you. Come on.
Ready and go!

459
00:29:28,477 --> 00:29:29,895
That's it.

460
00:29:32,064 --> 00:29:35,192
What is this? You
ready? I said go!

461
00:29:35,692 --> 00:29:38,612
If those are the best behaviors,
I'd hate to see the worst.

462
00:29:42,074 --> 00:29:43,325
May I help you?

463
00:29:43,742 --> 00:29:45,494
Are you looking
for somebody?

464
00:29:45,577 --> 00:29:49,081
No, I don't think you can. I'm
looking for someone in authority.

465
00:29:49,122 --> 00:29:52,835
Well, I'm Dr. Morgan,
the senior biologist.

466
00:29:52,960 --> 00:29:54,002
Oh.

467
00:29:55,587 --> 00:29:56,755
Really?

468
00:30:00,425 --> 00:30:02,594
Charming. Philip FitzRoyce.

469
00:30:02,678 --> 00:30:04,429
I know you.
I know your work.

470
00:30:04,513 --> 00:30:07,724
We were at that Law of the Sea
Conference together last summer.

471
00:30:07,766 --> 00:30:10,769
Oh yes, that's right.
Helsinki. Save the Whales.

472
00:30:10,811 --> 00:30:12,145
They made a hero out of me.

473
00:30:12,229 --> 00:30:14,481
Yeah, you know what
I never understood?

474
00:30:14,565 --> 00:30:17,276
Why did you ram
that Japanese whaler?

475
00:30:17,609 --> 00:30:21,697
(CHUCKLING) Because he got
in my way, ruined my best shot.

476
00:30:22,114 --> 00:30:24,783
Yeah. I was impressed.

477
00:30:26,952 --> 00:30:31,456
Good. Then perhaps we can have
a drink and some dinner tonight?

478
00:30:33,125 --> 00:30:37,671
Oh, I'm sorry, Mr. FitzRoyce,
but, that's a behavior I just don't do.

479
00:30:38,213 --> 00:30:39,506
(LAUGHING)

480
00:30:40,966 --> 00:30:44,595
Nice spins, Danny. I'll
meet you at the holding tank.

481
00:30:47,055 --> 00:30:48,515
Hey, aqua girl!

482
00:30:48,599 --> 00:30:49,850
Hi, Mike!

483
00:30:50,642 --> 00:30:51,643
Five.

484
00:31:02,362 --> 00:31:03,363
(GRUNTING)

485
00:31:03,488 --> 00:31:05,949
He don't sleep in,
he don't live in.

486
00:31:06,450 --> 00:31:09,369
Tell Shelby Overman for me
he can take a flyin' leap

487
00:31:09,453 --> 00:31:12,497
at a rollin' doughnut on a
gravel driveway, you hear?

488
00:31:12,581 --> 00:31:15,375
Hold it just a second. Didn't
he come home last night?

489
00:31:15,459 --> 00:31:17,502
He didn't show
up here either. No.

490
00:31:17,586 --> 00:31:18,837
I figure he's
home hung over.

491
00:31:18,879 --> 00:31:22,090
I tell you, the man's trash, and I
don't want him around my place!

492
00:31:22,174 --> 00:31:24,343
He's gone.
You take his stuff.

493
00:31:24,426 --> 00:31:25,677
Charlene,
what's goin' on, huh?

494
00:31:25,761 --> 00:31:27,512
Shelby Overman's AWOL again.

495
00:31:27,596 --> 00:31:29,514
Oh, no. I'm sorry.

496
00:31:29,806 --> 00:31:30,849
What, is this
all his stuff?

497
00:31:30,933 --> 00:31:33,185
Yeah. Doesn't figure.

498
00:31:33,435 --> 00:31:36,897
He left his passport and
his... And his credit cards.

499
00:31:36,980 --> 00:31:39,942
Driver's license,
pawn tickets.

500
00:31:40,525 --> 00:31:43,487
I don't think he could have
been planning to go too far.

501
00:31:43,528 --> 00:31:45,030
You don't think
something happened to him?

502
00:31:45,072 --> 00:31:46,573
I mean, wouldn't the
police have called...

503
00:31:46,657 --> 00:31:50,702
No. No, look. He is curled
up, drunk someplace.

504
00:31:50,744 --> 00:31:53,205
And when I find him,
he's in deep trouble.

505
00:31:53,288 --> 00:31:55,415
Don't you worry. We'll let you
know as soon as we hear anything.

506
00:31:55,499 --> 00:31:56,500
Wanna help me out?

507
00:31:56,541 --> 00:31:58,043
Yeah. Take care, Charlene.

508
00:31:58,585 --> 00:31:59,586
Help me look in the lagoon?

509
00:31:59,670 --> 00:32:00,837
You bet.

510
00:32:00,879 --> 00:32:04,257
Hey, I'm mad at that old boy,
but I don't mean him any harm.

511
00:32:04,341 --> 00:32:07,219
You hear me?
I don't mean him any harm!

512
00:32:14,059 --> 00:32:15,811
Down a little more.

513
00:32:16,353 --> 00:32:17,562
Turn it.

514
00:32:21,817 --> 00:32:23,777
Batteries are
fully charged, Mike.

515
00:32:23,860 --> 00:32:24,903
Thank you, Danny.

516
00:32:24,945 --> 00:32:26,279
Thanks, Danny.

517
00:32:28,657 --> 00:32:31,952
Control room, submersible
is now entering the lagoon.

518
00:32:32,160 --> 00:32:34,037
Roger. I can
monitor it from here.

519
00:32:34,079 --> 00:32:35,205
<i>Thank you.</i>

520
00:32:36,039 --> 00:32:39,084
TECHNICIAN: <i>(ON RADIO) Testing,
one, two, three. Can you read me, Kay?</i>

521
00:32:39,167 --> 00:32:41,545
KAY: <i>(ON RADIO) I read you.
Communications fine.</i>

522
00:32:42,295 --> 00:32:45,090
<i>For Charlene's sake,
I sure hope he's all right.</i>

523
00:32:53,598 --> 00:32:55,934
MIKE: <i>(ON RADIO)
There's Cindy or Sandy?</i>

524
00:32:55,976 --> 00:32:57,894
<i>I don't know how
to tell them apart.</i>

525
00:32:57,936 --> 00:33:00,105
KAY: <i>Cindy's a lot larger.</i>

526
00:33:08,655 --> 00:33:10,741
MIKE: <i>Control, this
is Venture One.</i>

527
00:33:11,241 --> 00:33:14,077
<i>We're at 25 feet, headed
for the Spanish Galleon.</i>

528
00:33:16,955 --> 00:33:19,291
I can see you now.
Hi, Mike.

529
00:33:41,313 --> 00:33:44,983
<i>Overman broke divers' rules
last night, out there.</i>

530
00:33:45,025 --> 00:33:47,652
<i>Went down to shackle
the sea gate alone.</i>

531
00:33:47,694 --> 00:33:51,156
<i>If anything happened to him, the ocean
current would have washed him up here,</i>

532
00:33:51,239 --> 00:33:53,283
<i>toward the center
of the lagoon.</i>

533
00:33:56,328 --> 00:33:58,246
KAY: <i>What about
the filtration pipes?</i>

534
00:33:58,497 --> 00:34:00,499
MIKE: <i>No, it's too strong a
current moving the other way.</i>

535
00:34:00,540 --> 00:34:02,167
<i>See, the flow's all
into the lagoon.</i>

536
00:34:02,250 --> 00:34:05,212
<i>There's a million gallons of
fresh salt water every hour.</i>

537
00:34:11,009 --> 00:34:14,304
KAY: <i>You think he could have gotten
trapped in the Spanish Galleon?</i>

538
00:34:14,346 --> 00:34:16,681
MIKE: <i>He could have gotten
caught in the superstructure.</i>

539
00:34:16,765 --> 00:34:18,683
<i>Would have kept him
from floating topside.</i>

540
00:34:19,559 --> 00:34:22,187
KAY: <i>Mike! Oh, God.
For a second I thought...</i>

541
00:34:22,312 --> 00:34:25,899
MIKE: <i>Yeah, yeah- I know it-
We call him Oscar.</i>

542
00:34:39,663 --> 00:34:42,541
<i>You stay here, Kay. I'll go into
the galleon and take a closer look.</i>

543
00:34:42,624 --> 00:34:44,251
KAY: <i>Uh-uh, Mike.
I'm goin' with you.</i>

544
00:34:48,588 --> 00:34:51,842
MIKE: <i>Goddamn dolphins!
What the hell are they doing?</i>

545
00:34:51,883 --> 00:34:55,053
KAY: <i>I don't know. They've been
acting strange for the last two days.</i>

546
00:34:55,929 --> 00:34:57,013
Look at 'em.

547
00:35:07,399 --> 00:35:09,693
KAY: <i>Control,
we're leaving the sub.</i>

548
00:35:09,901 --> 00:35:11,444
<i>We'll be out
of radio contact.</i>

549
00:35:11,528 --> 00:35:12,821
Read you,
Dr. Morgan.

550
00:35:13,029 --> 00:35:15,073
MIKE: <i>Grab your ABS bottles,
Kay- Let's go.</i>

551
00:35:15,532 --> 00:35:16,825
KAY: <i>Okay, sweetie.</i>

552
00:36:09,419 --> 00:36:11,129
(SQUEAKING EXCITEDLY)

553
00:36:15,800 --> 00:36:17,677
(SQUEAKING)

554
00:36:26,144 --> 00:36:27,145
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

555
00:36:34,611 --> 00:36:36,279
(MUFFLED EXCHANGE)

556
00:36:51,253 --> 00:36:53,296
MIKE: (MUFFLED) Go!
KAY: (MUFFLED) Go!

557
00:37:12,482 --> 00:37:15,068
(SHARK THEME PLAYING)

558
00:37:16,695 --> 00:37:19,489
KAY: Mike! Quick! Mike!

559
00:37:35,755 --> 00:37:38,300
The gate! Get the gate!
Shark!

560
00:37:38,550 --> 00:37:40,218
<i>God!
What's happening?</i>

561
00:37:45,640 --> 00:37:46,683
DAN: Close, damn it! Close!

562
00:37:49,561 --> 00:37:50,770
MIKE: Shit!

563
00:37:51,396 --> 00:37:53,732
Oh, God! Are you okay?
What the hell was that?

564
00:37:53,773 --> 00:37:55,859
Yeah! What is that?
You okay?

565
00:37:56,401 --> 00:37:58,737
My Guv'nor's
the 16th Earl of Haddenfield.

566
00:37:59,362 --> 00:38:02,240
Shake hands with the
first Calvin of SeaWorld.

567
00:38:02,741 --> 00:38:05,452
Enchante. Enchante.
He know French too, huh?

568
00:38:05,535 --> 00:38:07,746
Excuse me, gentlemen.
Mr. Bouchard...

569
00:38:07,829 --> 00:38:09,664
Wait a minute.
We're havin' dinner here.

570
00:38:09,748 --> 00:38:11,583
This better be important.
It is, sir.

571
00:38:12,417 --> 00:38:14,586
(WHISPERING) Mike and Dr. Morgan
were pursued by a renegade shark

572
00:38:14,669 --> 00:38:15,670
that got into our lagoon.

573
00:38:16,087 --> 00:38:18,298
It is important, gentlemen.
Better come with me.

574
00:38:24,763 --> 00:38:27,182
KAY: Believe me, Calvin,
it was a great white.

575
00:38:27,265 --> 00:38:30,060
It was about ten feet long, it was
exhibiting a typical feeding pattern.

576
00:38:30,268 --> 00:38:31,269
On us, Calvin!

577
00:38:31,353 --> 00:38:32,896
The damn thing tried
to feed on us. Exactly.

578
00:38:32,937 --> 00:38:34,397
Now look.
Where is it?

579
00:38:34,439 --> 00:38:35,690
Right here.

580
00:38:40,028 --> 00:38:41,154
Huh?

581
00:38:41,237 --> 00:38:44,115
(WHISTLING) You know, Cal,
this could be a stroke of luck.

582
00:38:45,950 --> 00:38:48,328
If we kill this beastie
on camera,

583
00:38:49,204 --> 00:38:51,706
I can guarantee you
media coverage.

584
00:38:53,833 --> 00:38:56,252
Lure him into a staging area,

585
00:38:56,294 --> 00:38:59,464
and at the precise moment,
slit his belly wide open.

586
00:39:01,633 --> 00:39:02,634
Can you do that?

587
00:39:02,717 --> 00:39:04,969
You try and stop him, mate.

588
00:39:05,053 --> 00:39:06,429
That's how we earn our bread.

589
00:39:06,471 --> 00:39:07,680
(CHUCKLING)

590
00:39:09,641 --> 00:39:12,977
Well, Jack is oversimplifying
matters, as is usual.

591
00:39:14,312 --> 00:39:16,648
But, yeah, I can do that.

592
00:39:16,689 --> 00:39:18,441
KAY: No!
MIKE: No?

593
00:39:18,817 --> 00:39:20,318
What do you mean, no?

594
00:39:20,860 --> 00:39:23,071
Well, I don't know if it's
occurred to any of you all,

595
00:39:23,154 --> 00:39:27,283
but there isn't a great white
alive in captivity anywhere.

596
00:39:27,992 --> 00:39:30,662
Now, we're unique here,
Calvin, you know that.

597
00:39:30,703 --> 00:39:33,456
If any facility can
maintain a white, it's us.

598
00:39:33,665 --> 00:39:37,377
If we could dart him, tranquilize him,
we could get him in a holding tank...

599
00:39:37,460 --> 00:39:41,131
Hold it! This is crazy,
this is nuts.

600
00:39:42,257 --> 00:39:44,342
White sharks are killers.
I know 'em.

601
00:39:44,843 --> 00:39:46,970
My father,
my brother, myself.

602
00:39:47,470 --> 00:39:49,556
They're murderers. No, Kay.

603
00:39:50,390 --> 00:39:54,269
Calvin, they die
magnificently.

604
00:39:55,895 --> 00:39:57,147
(LAUGHING)

605
00:39:57,814 --> 00:40:01,109
That would really be a spectacular
event. No doubt about that, huh?

606
00:40:04,529 --> 00:40:07,323
What are we doing, Calvin,
planning a network special?

607
00:40:08,616 --> 00:40:11,744
Don't you realize that we could
be the first people on the planet

608
00:40:11,828 --> 00:40:13,830
to have a
great white alive.

609
00:40:14,539 --> 00:40:17,375
Not if my Guv'nor
gets it first, miss.

610
00:40:18,084 --> 00:40:21,671
Okay. Say he kills it.
Well, that's it.

611
00:40:21,963 --> 00:40:23,381
It's one shot, over, gone.

612
00:40:24,883 --> 00:40:28,761
But a live great white. Now,
you think about that, Calvin!

613
00:40:29,262 --> 00:40:33,308
Nightly bulletins on the
progress of the killer shark.

614
00:40:33,850 --> 00:40:37,061
Pictures of us nursing it
back to health

615
00:40:37,145 --> 00:40:38,563
and lowering it
into a holding tank.

616
00:40:38,646 --> 00:40:40,356
Now, that's world news!

617
00:40:41,024 --> 00:40:42,901
Think of the lines
at the gate.

618
00:40:43,443 --> 00:40:45,653
Then you miss
the sport of the kill.

619
00:40:45,737 --> 00:40:48,198
Now, wait up, Jack.
Wait up.

620
00:40:49,157 --> 00:40:51,576
PHILIP: <i>Killing is
guaranteed press.</i>

621
00:40:51,659 --> 00:40:54,162
<i>But this other is much,
much more interesting.</i>

622
00:41:06,466 --> 00:41:08,343
DAN: Okay,
this is MS-222.

623
00:41:10,261 --> 00:41:13,181
This is quinaldine, but I had
to guesstimate the dosage.

624
00:41:13,264 --> 00:41:14,432
Kathy?

625
00:41:14,891 --> 00:41:16,684
Right. Thanks, Danny.

626
00:41:18,394 --> 00:41:21,189
All right, we're ready
in Control. You all set?

627
00:41:21,773 --> 00:41:23,191
MIKE: (ON RADIO)
<i>We're ready down here.</i>

628
00:41:23,775 --> 00:41:25,527
(KAY CLEARING THROAT)

629
00:41:25,777 --> 00:41:28,780
Well, with those
TV monitors rolling,

630
00:41:28,821 --> 00:41:30,823
you're gonna have more coverage
than a space launch around here.

631
00:41:30,907 --> 00:41:33,201
Good. Just the
way I like it. Right.

632
00:41:33,284 --> 00:41:35,328
The color of your wet suit's
one hell of a choice.

633
00:41:35,411 --> 00:41:36,788
The shark's gonna love you.

634
00:41:36,829 --> 00:41:38,122
Exactly.

635
00:41:38,206 --> 00:41:39,791
It helps me
get the close-ups.

636
00:41:39,832 --> 00:41:41,084
You're the showman.
(EXHALING)

637
00:41:41,834 --> 00:41:44,295
Honey, you think this
suit's gonna protect you?

638
00:41:44,337 --> 00:41:45,713
Are you kidding?
Have you felt the...

639
00:41:45,797 --> 00:41:48,633
It won't bite through,
but it will yield to pressure.

640
00:41:48,716 --> 00:41:51,135
So she might just get
a little squeeze.

641
00:41:52,595 --> 00:41:56,391
Oh, that's great news. Look,
why do you have to do this?

642
00:41:57,225 --> 00:42:00,144
Why don't you let Her Majesty's
number one son take care of it, huh?

643
00:42:00,186 --> 00:42:02,438
Because it's my job,
remember?

644
00:42:02,855 --> 00:42:04,566
Yeah, but I just don't
want it to be you.

645
00:42:04,649 --> 00:42:10,488
Look, you build all the stuff, I swim
around in it. That was the deal. Right?

646
00:42:10,530 --> 00:42:11,614
Hmm?

647
00:42:13,324 --> 00:42:14,909
I love you, too.

648
00:42:21,708 --> 00:42:25,169
If we get into any trouble, all
we have to do is pull the pin.

649
00:42:26,963 --> 00:42:28,506
What are those?
JACK: Mills bombs.

650
00:42:28,590 --> 00:42:30,925
What?
Mills bombs, sonny.

651
00:42:31,009 --> 00:42:35,138
Grenades. A chap in Her Majesty's
ordnance makes them up for me.

652
00:42:35,513 --> 00:42:38,182
<i>(ON RAADIO) Baby claymores.
Good horizontal dispersion.</i>

653
00:42:38,266 --> 00:42:41,060
<i>Some concussion. A bit rough on
the eardrums, but they do the trick.</i>

654
00:42:41,269 --> 00:42:43,605
Well, not in my water.
Take 'em off.

655
00:42:44,022 --> 00:42:46,524
You tend to your knitting, my
dear, and I shall tend to mine.

656
00:42:46,608 --> 00:42:49,068
MIKE: Hold it.
Hold on a second there.

657
00:42:49,277 --> 00:42:51,195
There's not gonna be
any explosives underwater.

658
00:42:51,279 --> 00:42:53,698
There's acrylic down there,
it's a very fragile environment.

659
00:42:53,781 --> 00:42:55,199
There's no bombs.

660
00:42:55,366 --> 00:42:57,285
PHILIP: <i>Look, Brody, I do
understand. This is insurance...</i>

661
00:42:57,368 --> 00:43:00,079
MIKE: <i>No, I don't think you
understood me here, FitzRoyce!</i>

662
00:43:00,872 --> 00:43:03,207
<i>I spent two years building
this park, and I'm not gonna see</i>

663
00:43:03,249 --> 00:43:05,752
<i>some visiting fireman with a
homemade bomb blow it up</i>

664
00:43:05,835 --> 00:43:07,045
<i>just because he wants
to kill a fish!</i>

665
00:43:08,421 --> 00:43:10,965
Calvin, are you
listening to all this?

666
00:43:11,549 --> 00:43:13,635
No grenades.

667
00:43:17,388 --> 00:43:20,475
For Christ's sake, Guv'nor.
Remember Australia?

668
00:43:21,184 --> 00:43:22,602
Oh, don't worry, Jack.

669
00:43:22,685 --> 00:43:24,979
After all, it's only
a little fish.

670
00:43:25,271 --> 00:43:26,689
Son of a...

671
00:43:27,523 --> 00:43:29,400
The pin has to be pulled.

672
00:43:29,484 --> 00:43:32,195
Right. Get rid
of this stuff.

673
00:43:32,236 --> 00:43:34,989
Everybody aboard here?
Let's get going.

674
00:43:37,241 --> 00:43:38,743
Shove off.

675
00:43:55,802 --> 00:43:57,845
KAY: <i>I need one clean
belly shot.</i>

676
00:43:58,054 --> 00:44:00,848
<i>If I miss on the first pass,
I'm gonna have to reload</i>

677
00:44:00,932 --> 00:44:02,934
<i>and just hope I get him
with the second dart.</i>

678
00:44:04,227 --> 00:44:06,270
PHILIP: This is a good
place to start.

679
00:44:08,439 --> 00:44:10,066
(ENGINES STOPPING)

680
00:44:10,108 --> 00:44:11,275
MIKE: Hit the lights.

681
00:44:15,697 --> 00:44:17,156
Shall we dance?

682
00:44:17,490 --> 00:44:21,786
Yeah, why not? I'm beginning to feel
like King Richard going to the Crusades.

683
00:44:26,874 --> 00:44:29,293
PHILIP: Ready, Jack?
Get the gear.

684
00:44:32,213 --> 00:44:34,424
JACK:
Brown bread, Guv'nor.

685
00:44:37,593 --> 00:44:39,178
You all right?

686
00:44:39,262 --> 00:44:40,638
Good luck.

687
00:45:33,274 --> 00:45:34,776
You know you only
get one shot.

688
00:45:34,859 --> 00:45:36,944
MIKE: Yeah, I know.
I know.

689
00:45:38,029 --> 00:45:39,530
(MIKE EXHALING)

690
00:45:40,448 --> 00:45:42,200
What about Kathryn?

691
00:45:43,201 --> 00:45:46,788
It'll stick in the shark. Hit
her, and it'll go right through.

692
00:45:47,330 --> 00:45:49,749
Just buoy him up,
slow him down, right?

693
00:45:51,417 --> 00:45:53,711
Dorsal fin,
middle of the back.

694
00:45:59,550 --> 00:46:01,219
Seen anything yet?

695
00:46:02,220 --> 00:46:04,263
Yeah, we'll get him
on the monitors.

696
00:46:23,991 --> 00:46:26,202
(KAY GRUNTING)

697
00:46:27,036 --> 00:46:28,955
(KAY SCREAMING)

698
00:46:50,726 --> 00:46:53,354
Quick! Mike,
he's making a run!

699
00:46:56,899 --> 00:46:58,276
Quick, shoot him!

700
00:46:59,110 --> 00:47:00,444
PHILIP: He's getting away!

701
00:47:01,320 --> 00:47:02,405
Damn it!

702
00:47:06,033 --> 00:47:07,827
MIKE: Get out of
the way, Kay!

703
00:47:08,703 --> 00:47:09,745
KAY: Now!

704
00:47:34,562 --> 00:47:35,646
Come on.

705
00:47:37,148 --> 00:47:38,941
Right. There you go.

706
00:47:38,983 --> 00:47:40,359
You did it, baby.
You did it.

707
00:47:40,443 --> 00:47:41,694
DAN: Here's the ladder.
Hold on.

708
00:47:41,777 --> 00:47:44,113
Come on.
Give me your fins.

709
00:47:44,155 --> 00:47:46,198
Give me your fins.
Let's go!

710
00:47:47,033 --> 00:47:48,659
DAN: Up you go.

711
00:47:50,620 --> 00:47:52,121
You all right?

712
00:47:54,624 --> 00:47:55,833
(GASPS)

713
00:47:56,375 --> 00:47:57,543
Close one back there.

714
00:47:57,627 --> 00:47:58,753
MIKE: Let's get
this stuff off her.

715
00:47:58,836 --> 00:47:59,837
LIZ: Kay, that was great!

716
00:47:59,921 --> 00:48:02,173
What am I,
a bloody porter?

717
00:48:02,256 --> 00:48:03,841
How about a hand
with this hardware?

718
00:48:03,883 --> 00:48:05,301
No, first things
first, Jacko.

719
00:48:05,343 --> 00:48:07,178
Mustn't ignore the ladies.

720
00:48:07,219 --> 00:48:09,180
And don't ignore
the bleedin' help.

721
00:48:09,221 --> 00:48:10,431
MIKE: Looked pretty
hairy down there.

722
00:48:10,514 --> 00:48:12,767
LIZ: You all right, Kay? For
a second, I was so worried.

723
00:48:12,850 --> 00:48:15,227
You sure know how
to scare the hell out of me.

724
00:48:15,728 --> 00:48:19,732
Be sure he's wrapped, okay?
Keep him wet. Let's get him in a tank.

725
00:48:20,858 --> 00:48:24,070
CALVIN: <i>(ON SPEAKER) Film
all right? TV picture looked cloudy.</i>

726
00:48:25,988 --> 00:48:30,159
Calvin. Kathryn's fine,
Philip is fine, Jack is fine.

727
00:48:30,201 --> 00:48:32,536
<i>Dan and Liz are fine.
I am okay too.</i>

728
00:48:32,578 --> 00:48:34,372
But, is the film okay?

729
00:48:34,956 --> 00:48:36,874
It's absolutely
first-rate, Cal.

730
00:48:36,958 --> 00:48:38,751
I think you'll
be very happy.

731
00:48:41,879 --> 00:48:43,756
Is everyone okay?

732
00:48:43,839 --> 00:48:45,424
It did look pretty
dangerous down there.

733
00:48:45,758 --> 00:48:48,636
Yeah, well, it looked pretty
dangerous from down here too, Calvin.

734
00:48:51,055 --> 00:48:53,724
KAY: We may have to work him
all night, keep him moving.

735
00:48:54,100 --> 00:48:57,853
Down, Danny.
Down, down. That's it.

736
00:48:58,729 --> 00:49:00,982
We have to be sure the oxygen
keeps running through his gills.

737
00:49:01,065 --> 00:49:03,025
We don't wanna lose him.

738
00:49:03,526 --> 00:49:04,902
(DOOR OPENING)

739
00:49:05,945 --> 00:49:10,157
Close the door! Whoever
you are, this is off limits.

740
00:49:12,702 --> 00:49:17,540
Liz, uh, get the hose running. I
wanna try aerating him, okay?

741
00:49:18,749 --> 00:49:21,085
Even to me,
the fearless harpoonist?

742
00:49:21,669 --> 00:49:23,004
Nah, you're okay.

743
00:49:24,755 --> 00:49:26,882
Come on in, sailor.
Are you new in town?

744
00:49:27,425 --> 00:49:30,970
Yeah. Came by to get me
a woman and a tattoo.

745
00:49:31,804 --> 00:49:33,347
Wanna see the tattoo?
(CHUCKLING)

746
00:49:34,265 --> 00:49:37,935
Well, I'd rather see the woman,
get a look at the competition.

747
00:49:38,936 --> 00:49:42,440
Sorry, there isn't any other
woman, there isn't any tattoo either.

748
00:49:43,733 --> 00:49:44,775
I'm lonely.

749
00:49:46,444 --> 00:49:48,029
<i>I'm sorry, darlin'.</i>

750
00:49:48,571 --> 00:49:49,780
Damn mammal.

751
00:49:50,990 --> 00:49:52,783
This one's a fish.

752
00:49:53,117 --> 00:49:57,038
A simple, beautiful fish.

753
00:50:01,500 --> 00:50:02,668
Okay.

754
00:50:02,835 --> 00:50:06,797
Mike! Mike! What are
you doing? Are you crazy?

755
00:50:07,465 --> 00:50:10,634
Liz, take a hike.
Okay.

756
00:50:10,801 --> 00:50:12,428
If this is the only way
we can be together,

757
00:50:12,470 --> 00:50:14,972
this is the only way
we can be together.

758
00:50:15,056 --> 00:50:18,809
Welcome aboard, sailor. Get
that hose and hold onto it, okay?

759
00:50:18,893 --> 00:50:20,895
Yeah. Okay.
Open the mouth.

760
00:50:21,270 --> 00:50:23,230
Say hi to your new friend.

761
00:50:23,439 --> 00:50:26,692
You know, this is the first time
you've ever done my work with me.

762
00:50:26,776 --> 00:50:28,652
Yeah, well,
it's a real thrill.

763
00:50:29,820 --> 00:50:31,405
Maybe tomorrow you
can come work with me

764
00:50:31,489 --> 00:50:33,824
and have some real excitement
help me pour foundations.

765
00:50:33,866 --> 00:50:35,201
(SCREAMING)

766
00:50:35,993 --> 00:50:38,454
Get away! Get clear!
Get clear!

767
00:50:42,917 --> 00:50:44,085
Whoa!

768
00:50:44,168 --> 00:50:45,753
Didn't he give
you any signs?

769
00:50:45,836 --> 00:50:48,798
No! One minute
he was dead out,

770
00:50:48,839 --> 00:50:50,508
the next minute
he was wide awake!

771
00:50:51,675 --> 00:50:53,385
No food.
No medication.

772
00:50:54,011 --> 00:50:57,681
It's the only live one in captivity,
guys. Let's keep him that way.

773
00:50:57,765 --> 00:51:01,310
Huh? Don't do anything
that's gonna traumatize him.

774
00:51:16,450 --> 00:51:18,202
(APPLAUSE)

775
00:51:20,955 --> 00:51:24,250
WOMAN: (ON PA) <i>Ahoy, mateys. Welcome
to the opening of the Undersea Kingdom.</i>

776
00:51:24,333 --> 00:51:27,878
<i>The magical mysteries of Jonah
and the Whale, the Coral Forest</i>

777
00:51:28,045 --> 00:51:29,755
<i>and the Sunken
Spanish Galleon.</i>

778
00:51:40,808 --> 00:51:42,226
Gotcha, Guv'nor!

779
00:51:50,234 --> 00:51:52,611
CALVIN: It's a whale with a
brain larger than most folks,

780
00:51:52,695 --> 00:51:55,072
able to earn beaucoup bucks
in a single bound.

781
00:51:55,114 --> 00:51:56,907
Kay and I went down
in the sub,

782
00:51:56,991 --> 00:51:58,576
and we searched
over all this area

783
00:51:58,659 --> 00:52:00,911
before the sharks hit us.

784
00:52:00,995 --> 00:52:04,123
Yeah, but Mike, what if Overman went
down on the other side of the sea gate?

785
00:52:04,415 --> 00:52:05,958
The tide might have
pulled him out,

786
00:52:06,041 --> 00:52:08,335
but we should have had a body
show up somewhere along the coast.

787
00:52:08,878 --> 00:52:11,005
Brody, did you check
the filtration pipe?

788
00:52:11,088 --> 00:52:14,258
No, Calvin. The current's
too strong goin' the other way.

789
00:52:14,341 --> 00:52:19,013
We got a million gallons of sea water
flowing into the lagoon every hour.

790
00:52:19,096 --> 00:52:21,849
The man's irresponsible.
When he turns up, fire him.

791
00:52:21,932 --> 00:52:23,684
Hold it, Calvin.
Hold it.

792
00:52:23,934 --> 00:52:26,729
He's a good man. He just
messes up every once in a while.

793
00:52:27,062 --> 00:52:29,565
I'm gonna hold
you responsible. Hmm?

794
00:52:35,029 --> 00:52:39,241
MAN: (ON PA) <i>And now, she gets to
ski by herself because Patty's the best.</i>

795
00:52:39,283 --> 00:52:42,244
How's it going, Leonard? I
just got today's first print-outs.

796
00:52:42,286 --> 00:52:45,748
Today, our advance sales are
three times ahead of our other parks.

797
00:52:45,789 --> 00:52:48,542
Not unexpected, Leonard.
Where's the great white now?

798
00:52:48,626 --> 00:52:51,128
In the tank room. I want to
put him on display at pool six.

799
00:52:51,212 --> 00:52:53,923
I wanna instruct everyone
to put all that information

800
00:52:53,964 --> 00:52:55,883
on all the welcomes,
rest stops and wrap-ups.

801
00:52:55,966 --> 00:52:58,886
But I thought we were to wait
on Dr. Morgan's word for that.

802
00:52:58,969 --> 00:53:02,932
Look. I run the park, I sell the
tickets and I make the decisions.

803
00:53:03,015 --> 00:53:04,391
Move the fish!

804
00:53:05,309 --> 00:53:07,978
I wanna be able to stand
in line to see it before three.

805
00:53:09,563 --> 00:53:13,359
ALL: Three and down,
and up, and turn.

806
00:53:17,655 --> 00:53:19,490
(WHOOPING)

807
00:53:19,531 --> 00:53:20,950
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

808
00:53:27,331 --> 00:53:28,999
MAN: (ON PA) <i>And now,
the SeaWorld water ski team</i>

809
00:53:29,041 --> 00:53:31,669
<i>in a dazzling display of
coordination and brilliance.</i>

810
00:53:32,670 --> 00:53:34,380
<i>The Silver Bullets!</i>

811
00:53:35,631 --> 00:53:37,341
All right!
Lookin' good!

812
00:53:39,218 --> 00:53:40,719
<i>There they go!</i>

813
00:53:48,060 --> 00:53:50,479
<i>Yeah! The helicopters!</i>

814
00:54:03,701 --> 00:54:04,910
Hi, Sean.
You were real hot.

815
00:54:05,786 --> 00:54:07,246
You were real hot.

816
00:54:07,329 --> 00:54:10,165
I want some time for us alone. You
got a few minutes between shows?

817
00:54:10,207 --> 00:54:11,959
You bet.
Great, Kelly.

818
00:54:12,042 --> 00:54:14,128
Listen.
Ready for some fun?

819
00:54:14,712 --> 00:54:16,714
Fantastic!
Let's ride the bumper boats.

820
00:54:16,755 --> 00:54:18,382
Bumper boats?

821
00:54:21,552 --> 00:54:22,886
WOMAN: Come on, it's fun.

822
00:54:22,970 --> 00:54:25,514
This is the entrance
to the Undersea Kingdom,

823
00:54:25,723 --> 00:54:28,017
an incredible complex
of underwater tunnels

824
00:54:28,225 --> 00:54:30,436
that show you first-hand
the miracles of the deep.

825
00:54:30,519 --> 00:54:33,063
There's no extra charge
for this unique attraction.

826
00:54:33,147 --> 00:54:36,692
Our underwater tunnels are
not only fun, but informative.

827
00:54:37,776 --> 00:54:39,194
Oh, look at that.

828
00:54:40,070 --> 00:54:43,282
ANNOUNCER: <i>Consumed alive in
history, Jonah found out what it was like</i>

829
00:54:43,365 --> 00:54:46,243
<i>to live in the belly of the
ocean's greatest animal.</i>

830
00:54:46,285 --> 00:54:50,706
<i>Our special Jonah and the Whale
showcase is at 11:00, 1:00 and 4:00</i>

831
00:54:50,748 --> 00:54:54,752
<i>in the amphitheater
inside the Undersea Kingdom.</i>

832
00:54:56,253 --> 00:54:57,296
(HISSING)

833
00:54:57,379 --> 00:54:59,256
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

834
00:55:01,800 --> 00:55:03,093
(MAN LAUGHS)

835
00:55:04,178 --> 00:55:05,929
(GIRLS LAUGHING)

836
00:55:09,058 --> 00:55:10,434
MAGNIFIED VOICE:
<i>This is Captain Sink.</i>

837
00:55:10,476 --> 00:55:13,687
<i>Welcome to my cave
of fun and surprises.</i>

838
00:55:14,563 --> 00:55:16,231
GIRLS: Oh, yuck!

839
00:55:17,191 --> 00:55:19,943
MIKE: I sure am gonna
miss these guys.

840
00:55:20,027 --> 00:55:21,904
How 'bout it, Casper?

841
00:55:22,112 --> 00:55:25,074
You wanna take the money and
run to Venezuela with old Mikey?

842
00:55:25,115 --> 00:55:28,827
Quieres un pescado?
You speak Spanish, huh?

843
00:55:29,244 --> 00:55:30,662
(LAUGHING)

844
00:55:31,163 --> 00:55:33,499
I think they're gonna
miss you, too.

845
00:55:34,875 --> 00:55:39,046
Now you and I are gonna have to
have a serious conversation sometime...

846
00:55:39,129 --> 00:55:41,256
About what's really goin' on.

847
00:55:41,298 --> 00:55:42,674
You and me.

848
00:55:43,467 --> 00:55:47,012
I know. I know.

849
00:55:47,096 --> 00:55:49,515
ANNOUNCER: <i>Mike Brody.
Mike Brody. Call your office, please.</i>

850
00:55:50,641 --> 00:55:53,060
See ya later.
(SEALS BARKING)

851
00:55:53,268 --> 00:55:55,437
MAN: (ON PA) <i>SeaWorld,
in honor of opening day...</i>

852
00:55:55,479 --> 00:55:57,314
(CASPER SCREECHING)
Oh, Casper.

853
00:55:58,565 --> 00:56:00,567
What's a girl to do, huh?

854
00:56:01,485 --> 00:56:02,986
Thank you.

855
00:56:03,028 --> 00:56:05,823
MAN: (ON PA) <i>A great white
shark in holding pool number six.</i>

856
00:56:05,906 --> 00:56:10,119
<i>You will be able to view the one
and only great white in captivity.</i>

857
00:56:13,997 --> 00:56:16,542
WOMAN: (ON PA) <i>The great white
shark has roamed the ocean's depths</i>

858
00:56:16,625 --> 00:56:17,876
<i>for millions of years.</i>

859
00:56:17,960 --> 00:56:19,378
<i>A proud animal...</i>

860
00:56:19,461 --> 00:56:21,380
Excuse me. Oh, God!

861
00:56:21,463 --> 00:56:23,549
<i>While alone,
is a predator...</i>

862
00:56:24,425 --> 00:56:26,885
Excuse me!
What is he doing here?

863
00:56:27,052 --> 00:56:28,095
Calvin ordered him moved.

864
00:56:28,178 --> 00:56:31,723
Why didn't he ask me? Why
did he go ahead on his own?

865
00:56:32,182 --> 00:56:34,935
WOMAN: (ON PA) <i>This shark,
a first of its kind to be held...</i>

866
00:56:35,102 --> 00:56:37,187
No, Danny! Danny!

867
00:56:40,941 --> 00:56:43,152
Liz, get a hose ready,
I wanna aerate him now!

868
00:56:44,194 --> 00:56:45,446
Come on, Danny. Get the back.

869
00:56:45,529 --> 00:56:47,948
WOMAN: <i>Just a minute.
Please remain calm.</i>

870
00:56:48,031 --> 00:56:51,368
<i>That's Dr. Morgan and
assistant members of our staff.</i>

871
00:56:51,410 --> 00:56:53,787
<i>Uh, please don't interfere
in any way.</i>

872
00:56:55,706 --> 00:56:57,040
Excuse me.

873
00:56:57,124 --> 00:56:59,293
KAY: Liz! Liz!

874
00:57:00,335 --> 00:57:01,795
Come on, boy.

875
00:57:05,883 --> 00:57:08,093
That's it. Come on.
Turn it, Danny.

876
00:57:09,678 --> 00:57:12,598
Shit!
Come on. Come on!

877
00:57:12,681 --> 00:57:15,767
No. Boy, come on!

878
00:57:31,450 --> 00:57:32,784
Excuse me.

879
00:57:37,748 --> 00:57:40,751
WOMAN: (ON PA) <i>Let me bring
your attention to some other events...</i>

880
00:57:40,792 --> 00:57:42,419
PHILIP: Kathryn.

881
00:57:42,461 --> 00:57:44,755
<i>The seal and otter show
and of course...</i>

882
00:57:44,838 --> 00:57:46,089
Kathryn.

883
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:51,011
Bad luck.

884
00:57:51,386 --> 00:57:52,763
(SIGHING)

885
00:57:57,976 --> 00:58:00,771
Go ahead.
Photograph it.

886
00:58:03,941 --> 00:58:05,984
Look out!
Kelly. Kelly.

887
00:58:06,068 --> 00:58:09,071
I don't know.
I don't. No. No.

888
00:58:09,112 --> 00:58:12,157
Come on, you'll love it.
It's fun. Trust me. Come on!

889
00:58:13,700 --> 00:58:15,994
What is this thing?
Are you sure?

890
00:58:16,078 --> 00:58:18,038
Are you sure
we should be doing this?

891
00:58:19,289 --> 00:58:22,376
Oh! Oh, God. Can
this hold two people?

892
00:58:23,418 --> 00:58:25,295
Oh. Push. Push.

893
00:58:25,420 --> 00:58:28,674
Oh, my God. Are you
steering this, or am I?

894
00:58:28,799 --> 00:58:31,176
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

895
00:58:31,426 --> 00:58:34,513
GO! Go! Get away! Get away!

896
00:58:43,772 --> 00:58:47,818
WOMAN: <i>We invite you to enter the magical
world of the deep water Coral Forest</i>

897
00:58:47,859 --> 00:58:51,530
<i>where you may observe the wonders
of the deep without ever getting wet.</i>

898
00:58:51,613 --> 00:58:55,367
<i>The Spanish Galleon plays
host to a myriad of colorful fish</i>

899
00:58:55,450 --> 00:58:58,996
<i>that SeaWorld has assembled
from the different oceans of the world.</i>

900
00:59:02,624 --> 00:59:05,002
Look at all of them!
Oh, yeah!

901
00:59:05,043 --> 00:59:08,171
That looks like a butterfly.
You're right.

902
00:59:09,923 --> 00:59:12,092
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

903
00:59:19,016 --> 00:59:20,517
MAN: Oh, my God!
Look at that!

904
00:59:20,601 --> 00:59:21,602
(GIRLS SCREAMING)

905
00:59:26,189 --> 00:59:27,816
Look, Kay, I don't think
you want to see this.

906
00:59:27,858 --> 00:59:30,819
Mike, everybody is assuming
that this was a shark attack.

907
00:59:30,861 --> 00:59:32,863
No, I wanna make sure.
Okay. All right.

908
00:59:34,239 --> 00:59:35,991
Did you guys pull him out?

909
00:59:36,116 --> 00:59:37,701
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

910
01:00:00,390 --> 01:00:02,225
(RETCHING)

911
01:00:11,443 --> 01:00:13,320
That's Shelby Overman.

912
01:00:19,117 --> 01:00:20,410
Kay, I told...
Miss...

913
01:00:20,494 --> 01:00:21,828
Mike. Ray.

914
01:00:23,580 --> 01:00:27,250
If this was a shark attack,
I've seen it before.

915
01:00:29,378 --> 01:00:30,462
Okay?

916
01:00:41,723 --> 01:00:42,974
Oh, Mike.

917
01:00:44,935 --> 01:00:46,603
Oh, my God!

918
01:00:49,439 --> 01:00:52,317
Let's go find Calvin.
Come on! Come on!

919
01:00:52,526 --> 01:00:55,487
MAN: I'm getting a lot of contradictory
readings from the filtration pumps.

920
01:00:55,570 --> 01:00:57,072
LEONARD: Such as?

921
01:00:57,114 --> 01:00:59,700
High pump rate,
low outflow

922
01:00:59,783 --> 01:01:03,120
and a pressure build-up
on the inboard tunnel valve.

923
01:01:03,203 --> 01:01:06,206
That's number two.
Could be an obstruction.

924
01:01:06,665 --> 01:01:08,542
Well, that's not
my department.

925
01:01:08,625 --> 01:01:11,545
See if you can locate Brody
or Calvin, will you?

926
01:01:14,756 --> 01:01:15,882
CALVIN: Very posh.

927
01:01:15,966 --> 01:01:18,009
Yes, it's quite a display.

928
01:01:18,719 --> 01:01:22,723
Tell me. How do you contain the
sharks in this part of the lagoon?

929
01:01:22,931 --> 01:01:25,475
It's that old shark screen,
that bubble screen.

930
01:01:25,517 --> 01:01:28,145
You know,
sharks don't like that.

931
01:01:28,186 --> 01:01:31,148
It's what they call, uh, marine
segregation. (TELEPHONE RINGING)

932
01:01:32,065 --> 01:01:34,359
Dr. Bouchard. Telephone.

933
01:01:34,443 --> 01:01:36,945
Ah, excuse me, gentlemen.
Get comfortable now.

934
01:01:38,405 --> 01:01:40,031
Here you go, sir.

935
01:01:41,825 --> 01:01:43,160
Bouchard here.

936
01:01:44,786 --> 01:01:46,580
What about the pumps?

937
01:01:47,330 --> 01:01:51,168
Ah, nah, nah, nah.
Don't wait for Brody.

938
01:01:51,251 --> 01:01:55,422
Just, uh, shut down number two
pump and switch over to number one.

939
01:01:55,505 --> 01:01:57,007
Simple as that.

940
01:01:57,924 --> 01:02:01,553
Because it costs too much to
replace and they burn out, that's why!

941
01:02:01,636 --> 01:02:05,724
And tell Brody to get down here to the
Neptune Room on the double, y'hear?

942
01:02:08,268 --> 01:02:09,603
Thank you.
You're welcome.

943
01:02:14,775 --> 01:02:17,194
(SHARK THEME PLAYING)

944
01:02:19,362 --> 01:02:20,947
Well, gentlemen.

945
01:02:22,365 --> 01:02:23,366
Chin-chin.

946
01:02:23,408 --> 01:02:25,452
Oh, cheers.
Cheers.

947
01:02:27,621 --> 01:02:29,164
KAY: There they are.

948
01:02:31,958 --> 01:02:35,545
Calvin, I've got bad news.
Keep your voices down, sit down.

949
01:02:36,213 --> 01:02:37,506
Sit down!

950
01:02:39,424 --> 01:02:40,675
Was it the shark?

951
01:02:45,305 --> 01:02:46,556
It was a shark.

952
01:02:47,724 --> 01:02:49,142
It was a shark

953
01:02:49,810 --> 01:02:53,063
with a bite radius
about a yard across.

954
01:02:53,563 --> 01:02:57,901
Don't be silly. That would indicate
a shark of some 35 feet in length.

955
01:02:58,151 --> 01:02:59,903
You said it exactly.

956
01:03:05,534 --> 01:03:08,912
Our shark still has
all its teeth. Yeah.

957
01:03:08,995 --> 01:03:10,539
That means it was a baby.

958
01:03:10,831 --> 01:03:13,416
Our shark couldn't
have killed Overman.

959
01:03:14,668 --> 01:03:16,086
Its mother did.

960
01:03:16,878 --> 01:03:19,256
You talkin' about
some damn shark's mother?

961
01:03:19,673 --> 01:03:21,258
Calvin, don't you hear
what she's sayin' here?

962
01:03:21,341 --> 01:03:22,759
CALVIN: I'm listening!

963
01:03:23,009 --> 01:03:24,553
Now, if there is
such an animal,

964
01:03:24,594 --> 01:03:26,263
she gave birth way out to sea,

965
01:03:26,304 --> 01:03:27,597
and the baby swam
through the sea gate

966
01:03:27,639 --> 01:03:28,849
that you left open, Brody!

967
01:03:28,932 --> 01:03:34,271
No! Overman was killed
inside the park.

968
01:03:34,354 --> 01:03:37,274
The baby was caught
inside the park.

969
01:03:37,357 --> 01:03:40,777
Its mother is
inside the park.

970
01:03:54,499 --> 01:03:56,251
(ECHOING) She's right there!

971
01:03:57,002 --> 01:03:59,296
(SCREAMING)

972
01:04:06,636 --> 01:04:08,263
WOMAN: How did that
thing get in there?

973
01:04:08,722 --> 01:04:11,641
The animals are in
the lagoon! Ski show!

974
01:04:12,434 --> 01:04:13,935
Control, this is Bouchard.

975
01:04:13,977 --> 01:04:15,270
Now you listen
to me carefully!

976
01:04:15,312 --> 01:04:16,313
I want you to
clear the tunnel,

977
01:04:16,396 --> 01:04:17,647
I want you
to let the people out,

978
01:04:17,689 --> 01:04:19,649
I want you to close
the gate and seal the park!

979
01:04:19,733 --> 01:04:21,818
Seal the park!
I'll be down in a minute.

980
01:04:25,447 --> 01:04:26,823
MAN: Hey! Hey! Watch it!

981
01:04:26,907 --> 01:04:29,200
WOMAN: Who is that guy?
MAN: Watch out!

982
01:04:41,212 --> 01:04:44,716
Hey, bring it over here! Hey!

983
01:04:51,556 --> 01:04:54,726
All right. I've had enough
fun. Let's go in now.

984
01:04:54,809 --> 01:04:56,645
Come on. You're enjoying this.

985
01:04:56,686 --> 01:05:00,482
No. Look, don't you have
to be at work or something?

986
01:05:00,523 --> 01:05:03,151
Tammy's on the pyramid. I don't
have to be back till the second half.

987
01:05:03,193 --> 01:05:04,611
Come on.
Oh.

988
01:05:07,364 --> 01:05:08,448
Gotcha, lovers.

989
01:05:08,531 --> 01:05:10,158
Shit!
God.

990
01:05:11,868 --> 01:05:13,828
Get out! Get out!
Hey, what the?

991
01:05:13,870 --> 01:05:15,830
Hey, what are ya doin'?

992
01:05:17,832 --> 01:05:19,000
Brody!

993
01:05:20,335 --> 01:05:22,671
Get out of the water.
Get out!

994
01:05:22,712 --> 01:05:25,340
Get out of the water, please.
Please, come in from the water.

995
01:05:25,507 --> 01:05:27,634
Out of the water! Come on!
Get out of the water!

996
01:05:29,052 --> 01:05:30,887
Out of the water!

997
01:05:36,393 --> 01:05:37,394
Get out!

998
01:05:39,562 --> 01:05:40,605
Get outta the way!

999
01:05:44,401 --> 01:05:45,443
Shit!

1000
01:05:47,946 --> 01:05:49,280
(PHONE RINGING)

1001
01:05:52,867 --> 01:05:54,661
MAN: This is
SeaWorld Control.

1002
01:05:55,787 --> 01:05:56,997
Uh-huh.

1003
01:05:58,456 --> 01:06:00,917
Yes. I got him right here.

1004
01:06:05,755 --> 01:06:08,216
ANNOUNCER: <i>All right, boys.
Come on in and take a bow.</i>

1005
01:06:08,299 --> 01:06:10,552
<i>I apologize to have you...
No! Get</i> up <i>here!</i>

1006
01:06:11,219 --> 01:06:12,929
Get outta the water!
Get outta the water!

1007
01:06:15,765 --> 01:06:17,434
MIKE: Boys. Boys!

1008
01:06:18,101 --> 01:06:20,770
Bring the boat in!
Get outta the water!

1009
01:06:20,812 --> 01:06:23,440
You're gonna get both
of us fired out here!

1010
01:06:23,523 --> 01:06:25,859
Get out! Everybody out!

1011
01:06:25,942 --> 01:06:27,902
Gimme the mike!

1012
01:06:28,069 --> 01:06:29,112
Hey, Brody! Come back here!

1013
01:06:29,154 --> 01:06:32,323
<i>Get outta the water!
Bring it in.</i>

1014
01:06:32,407 --> 01:06:35,535
<i>Bring it in!
Bring the boat in!</i>

1015
01:06:35,618 --> 01:06:37,203
<i>Get out of the water
right now!</i>

1016
01:06:37,454 --> 01:06:39,205
Ready, up! One. Two.

1017
01:06:41,624 --> 01:06:44,335
MIKE: <i>Bring that boat in!
Get outta the water right now!</i>

1018
01:06:44,419 --> 01:06:47,172
Hey, get me down!
Just get me down!

1019
01:06:48,298 --> 01:06:50,383
Get me down!
What are you saying?

1020
01:06:50,467 --> 01:06:52,594
There's something back there!
A shark!

1021
01:06:53,386 --> 01:06:55,221
Bring your boat in!

1022
01:06:59,642 --> 01:07:01,394
(CROWD SCREAMING)

1023
01:07:01,978 --> 01:07:03,313
There's a shark!

1024
01:07:03,646 --> 01:07:06,149
(AUDIENCE SCREAMING)

1025
01:07:12,989 --> 01:07:14,824
(SCREAMING CONTINUING)

1026
01:07:15,492 --> 01:07:18,828
GIRLS: One, two, three,
four, five, six, seven.

1027
01:07:19,037 --> 01:07:21,623
MIKE: <i>Get outta the water!</i>

1028
01:07:24,793 --> 01:07:26,294
Oh, my God!

1029
01:07:27,420 --> 01:07:28,963
(ALL SCREAMING)

1030
01:07:29,339 --> 01:07:31,007
MIKE: Get outta the water!

1031
01:07:35,261 --> 01:07:36,763
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

1032
01:07:37,180 --> 01:07:38,431
Get out!

1033
01:07:38,848 --> 01:07:40,892
MAN: We're coming!
We're coming!

1034
01:07:41,059 --> 01:07:42,936
It's gonna eat us!

1035
01:07:43,103 --> 01:07:44,395
They'll die!

1036
01:07:47,482 --> 01:07:50,110
Gimme your hand. Come on!
Pull me out!

1037
01:07:54,405 --> 01:07:55,490
Hang on!

1038
01:08:01,996 --> 01:08:05,041
SEAN: Needs a choke
or something. Pull it.

1039
01:08:06,209 --> 01:08:07,961
(BOTH GASP)

1040
01:08:18,847 --> 01:08:20,223
SEAN: Hold my hand.

1041
01:08:20,765 --> 01:08:21,933
(SCREAMS)

1042
01:08:22,725 --> 01:08:24,602
SEAN: Kelly!
Shark!

1043
01:08:26,062 --> 01:08:27,397
Kelly!

1044
01:08:29,065 --> 01:08:30,483
(SCREAMS)

1045
01:08:33,111 --> 01:08:34,195
Kelly!

1046
01:08:42,120 --> 01:08:44,581
What the hell is that?
Shit! Hang on!

1047
01:09:02,098 --> 01:09:04,934
GIRL: What happened?
She's drowning! She's drowning!

1048
01:09:05,602 --> 01:09:09,230
Swim! Swim, kid, swim!

1049
01:09:11,941 --> 01:09:13,443
(PEOPLE GASPING)

1050
01:09:20,491 --> 01:09:22,202
PHILIP: Call an ambulance.

1051
01:09:22,285 --> 01:09:24,412
Quickly. Come on.
Get out of the way!

1052
01:09:24,454 --> 01:09:26,289
Give us some
room there, please.

1053
01:09:26,331 --> 01:09:27,332
Get a paramedic!

1054
01:09:28,583 --> 01:09:30,126
Look out, Mommy!

1055
01:09:37,175 --> 01:09:38,343
Kelly!

1056
01:09:38,426 --> 01:09:41,095
Did you call an ambulance?
Yeah, the paramedics.

1057
01:09:41,304 --> 01:09:43,223
MIKE: Twist that tourniquet
tight and hold it there.

1058
01:09:43,306 --> 01:09:44,724
Goddamn shark!

1059
01:09:45,683 --> 01:09:46,976
SEAN: I'm here.
You're gonna be okay.

1060
01:09:47,018 --> 01:09:48,311
MAN 1: There's still some
injured in the water.

1061
01:09:48,353 --> 01:09:49,479
MAN 2: They're bringin'
in the wounded.

1062
01:09:49,562 --> 01:09:51,356
MAN 3: The ambulance
is on the way.

1063
01:09:52,106 --> 01:09:54,984
Shall I leave the gate open?
Cindy and Sandy are out there.

1064
01:09:55,026 --> 01:09:56,486
Shit.

1065
01:09:58,613 --> 01:10:01,157
No. They're gonna have to
take care of themselves, Liz.

1066
01:10:02,033 --> 01:10:05,245
We can't take our chance
on that big bitch gettin' in.

1067
01:10:05,828 --> 01:10:08,998
Hey, you all right?
Yeah. Yeah. I'm fine.

1068
01:10:09,415 --> 01:10:11,668
Uh, I'm gonna go with Kelly.

1069
01:10:11,751 --> 01:10:13,002
I think you should.

1070
01:10:14,462 --> 01:10:17,882
What are you gonna do?
I don't know.

1071
01:10:22,470 --> 01:10:25,932
<i>Hello out there.
This is Calvin Bouchard.</i>

1072
01:10:26,182 --> 01:10:28,726
<i>May I please
have your kind attention.</i>

1073
01:10:29,185 --> 01:10:31,688
<i>Due to technical difficulties,</i>

1074
01:10:31,729 --> 01:10:35,024
<i>it has become necessary for us
to temporarily close</i>

1075
01:10:35,233 --> 01:10:36,818
<i>the Undersea Kingdom now.</i>

1076
01:10:37,193 --> 01:10:41,531
<i>For those of you all still in the
underwater portion of this park,</i>

1077
01:10:42,031 --> 01:10:44,701
<i>please follow your guides,</i>

1078
01:10:44,742 --> 01:10:48,830
<i>and they will point out the most
convenient and accessible exits.</i>

1079
01:10:49,622 --> 01:10:52,875
Where the hell is the nearest
accessible exit? We're underwater!

1080
01:10:53,710 --> 01:10:54,919
Is this off?
Uh-huh.

1081
01:10:55,712 --> 01:10:57,463
Gimme some lights down there!
Got them right here.

1082
01:10:57,547 --> 01:10:59,716
Can't see shit down there!

1083
01:10:59,757 --> 01:11:02,093
Get me some medical
attention here, quick!

1084
01:11:02,343 --> 01:11:03,720
<i>Okay, ladies and gentlemen,</i>

1085
01:11:03,803 --> 01:11:06,139
<i>you all heard the announcement,
so please follow me</i>

1086
01:11:06,222 --> 01:11:09,309
<i>in an orderly fashion,
and remember walk, do not run.</i>

1087
01:11:14,230 --> 01:11:16,232
Daddy, Daddy!
Look at the fish!

1088
01:11:17,984 --> 01:11:20,111
Look!
Holy shit!

1089
01:11:20,236 --> 01:11:22,196
(PANICKED SCREAMING)

1090
01:11:24,949 --> 01:11:26,826
(SCREAMING)

1091
01:11:40,631 --> 01:11:42,216
TECHNICIAN:
Tunnel failure, number six.

1092
01:11:44,802 --> 01:11:46,763
It's Jonah and the
Whale- That's it.

1093
01:11:46,804 --> 01:11:49,223
Tube integrity has been
compromised.

1094
01:11:49,265 --> 01:11:50,683
We've got leakage
and pressure loss.

1095
01:11:55,104 --> 01:11:56,272
We have to seal the section

1096
01:11:56,314 --> 01:11:57,857
or we'll lose
the whole complex.

1097
01:11:57,940 --> 01:12:01,110
Watertight doors.
Hit it. On automatic.

1098
01:12:01,611 --> 01:12:05,281
They're all on go status.
Activated. Now!

1099
01:12:05,865 --> 01:12:08,534
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

1100
01:12:12,663 --> 01:12:13,748
I need my wallet!

1101
01:12:16,751 --> 01:12:19,295
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

1102
01:12:42,693 --> 01:12:46,322
Quiet! Quiet! Please!

1103
01:12:46,364 --> 01:12:48,825
I need your attention,
please. Quiet!

1104
01:12:48,866 --> 01:12:52,703
Now the water is not going
any higher, so calm down, okay?

1105
01:12:52,787 --> 01:12:55,623
It's stopped. It's
stopped, so calm down.

1106
01:12:58,584 --> 01:13:01,337
GUIDE: <i>The oxygen that
we have in here is all we have,</i>

1107
01:13:01,379 --> 01:13:05,633
<i>so let's not panic, but let's try
to take shallow breaths, okay?</i>

1108
01:13:21,023 --> 01:13:23,025
Hey, Mike.
MIKE: Yeah!

1109
01:13:23,109 --> 01:13:26,487
This is our last cut. I think
our tunnel patch is ready to go.

1110
01:13:26,529 --> 01:13:29,240
Good. Rig the winch
on that work boat up there.

1111
01:13:29,323 --> 01:13:30,533
You got it.

1112
01:13:32,994 --> 01:13:35,496
How much longer,
sweetie? I don't know.

1113
01:13:35,538 --> 01:13:36,664
No?

1114
01:13:37,665 --> 01:13:40,418
We're gonna have to nudge
these tunnel sections together.

1115
01:13:40,501 --> 01:13:43,546
Then we're gonna slap on a patch
and we're gonna weld the whole thing.

1116
01:13:43,588 --> 01:13:44,881
Then we evacuate?

1117
01:13:44,922 --> 01:13:47,216
No, then we gotta put
pressure back into the tunnels,

1118
01:13:47,300 --> 01:13:50,470
then the watertight doors will
open up, then people go home.

1119
01:13:51,554 --> 01:13:54,307
Hey, watch how you're
cutting that thing! It's critical!

1120
01:13:54,390 --> 01:13:57,268
Relax. Relax. You're
doing everything you can.

1121
01:13:57,935 --> 01:13:59,645
Come on. Come over here.

1122
01:14:03,065 --> 01:14:05,568
Listen.
I've been thinking.

1123
01:14:06,402 --> 01:14:09,447
Maybe Venezuela can use
some trained whales, huh?

1124
01:14:10,948 --> 01:14:13,075
What? Are you serious?
Yeah.

1125
01:14:13,409 --> 01:14:15,411
I think this one's on me.

1126
01:14:15,453 --> 01:14:17,747
But next year...
I'll follow you anywhere.

1127
01:14:17,788 --> 01:14:19,415
Yeah!
I love you!

1128
01:14:20,917 --> 01:14:23,085
(CHATTERING)

1129
01:14:26,547 --> 01:14:27,548
Ah, Mr. Glass.

1130
01:14:27,965 --> 01:14:29,383
Is Mr. Bouchard
going to be here?

1131
01:14:29,967 --> 01:14:32,887
Please, please.
I have a statement to make.

1132
01:14:33,095 --> 01:14:34,805
Was there an explosion?
What about the fire?

1133
01:14:34,889 --> 01:14:36,265
How many people are missing?

1134
01:14:36,474 --> 01:14:39,310
Late this afternoon, as a
result of a minor disturbance,

1135
01:14:39,393 --> 01:14:42,104
there was a pressure failure in
one of the underwater tunnels

1136
01:14:42,146 --> 01:14:44,273
that are a major attraction
here at the park.

1137
01:14:44,815 --> 01:14:47,443
We estimate that
30 to 40 people

1138
01:14:47,693 --> 01:14:50,488
were in the process
of being evacuated

1139
01:14:50,571 --> 01:14:54,617
when the watertight safety doors
temporarily delayed their exit.

1140
01:14:55,243 --> 01:14:57,328
We're working right now
to release them

1141
01:14:57,411 --> 01:14:59,121
under the safest
possible circumstances.

1142
01:15:00,706 --> 01:15:03,709
In addition, seven visitors
were injured in our beach area.

1143
01:15:04,418 --> 01:15:05,628
That's all for now.
Give me a break, boys.

1144
01:15:05,711 --> 01:15:07,046
What is this we've heard
about a large shark?

1145
01:15:07,421 --> 01:15:10,841
I'll let you know as I know
more. A very large shark...

1146
01:15:11,801 --> 01:15:13,553
That's all. There is no more.

1147
01:15:14,512 --> 01:15:15,805
WOMAN: When will
they get this fixed?

1148
01:15:15,846 --> 01:15:17,557
GUIDE: I'm sure they're
working on it.

1149
01:15:18,140 --> 01:15:21,227
Stay together to keep warm.
I know you're cold.

1150
01:15:22,019 --> 01:15:27,066
Stay together, take shallow breaths
and concentrate on your breathing, okay?

1151
01:15:44,417 --> 01:15:45,835
Well, any sign
of mother?

1152
01:15:48,879 --> 01:15:49,880
Okay, then.

1153
01:15:51,966 --> 01:15:53,676
Where did the animal
hide the first time?

1154
01:15:55,303 --> 01:15:56,387
Uh...

1155
01:15:58,180 --> 01:15:59,765
Filtration pipe.

1156
01:16:00,349 --> 01:16:02,018
Opposite side of the lagoon.

1157
01:16:02,852 --> 01:16:06,731
Brody, is there an access
hatch, a backwash gate?

1158
01:16:08,733 --> 01:16:09,984
Heavy grill work.

1159
01:16:10,026 --> 01:16:12,528
Keeps the pumps clear when
we back-flush that system.

1160
01:16:12,612 --> 01:16:15,906
Why? What do you want to do?
Get that thing back in?

1161
01:16:17,241 --> 01:16:18,367
He's a bright lad.

1162
01:16:18,909 --> 01:16:23,664
Yes. Jack and I are going
to lure him back into the pipe,

1163
01:16:23,706 --> 01:16:27,793
close the gates and then
dispose of him at our leisure.

1164
01:16:27,877 --> 01:16:29,545
Meanwhile, you can weld
your tunnel patch

1165
01:16:29,629 --> 01:16:31,922
and then Calvin can
evacuate the civilians.

1166
01:16:33,090 --> 01:16:35,259
What if she doesn't
want to go back in?

1167
01:16:36,344 --> 01:16:39,388
Oh, I think we can pretty much
guarantee she'll want to go back in.

1168
01:16:39,430 --> 01:16:41,223
Don't you, Jack?
Sure.

1169
01:16:42,475 --> 01:16:44,393
Just how are you
going to guarantee that?

1170
01:16:46,562 --> 01:16:47,897
Live bait.

1171
01:16:48,981 --> 01:16:50,358
MAN: We're ready to move
out over the tunnel now.

1172
01:16:51,901 --> 01:16:52,943
MIKE: Let's go.

1173
01:17:04,622 --> 01:17:06,082
I'll be in the
Control Room.

1174
01:17:06,666 --> 01:17:08,250
I'll go with you.

1175
01:17:10,961 --> 01:17:12,588
MAN: Give me that.
Let me stow it over here.

1176
01:17:14,924 --> 01:17:15,925
No, I got it.

1177
01:17:17,176 --> 01:17:18,844
TECHNICIAN: Yeah,
we're on top of it.

1178
01:17:18,928 --> 01:17:20,262
Okay. Thanks.

1179
01:17:28,938 --> 01:17:30,940
Now, where's
that damn fish?

1180
01:17:34,026 --> 01:17:35,277
There. I've got him.

1181
01:17:36,028 --> 01:17:38,155
Sorry, it's just the dolphins.

1182
01:17:41,117 --> 01:17:42,952
Babies, stay out
of it, please.

1183
01:17:44,245 --> 01:17:45,830
And I've rigged
a lifeline.

1184
01:17:46,956 --> 01:17:50,751
Just let the pumps push you out and
use the rope to pull yourself back in.

1185
01:17:51,252 --> 01:17:52,253
Right.

1186
01:17:53,838 --> 01:17:55,923
And why don't
I do all the filming?

1187
01:17:58,050 --> 01:18:00,761
I want both cameras. We need
the coverage. Come on, Jack!

1188
01:18:01,721 --> 01:18:03,013
This isn't a picnic.

1189
01:18:03,472 --> 01:18:05,933
This film is a bloody
retirement annuity.

1190
01:18:07,560 --> 01:18:09,895
I'd feel better if you
did just the one thing.

1191
01:18:10,438 --> 01:18:11,814
What's the matter?

1192
01:18:12,440 --> 01:18:13,482
Getting cold feet?

1193
01:18:21,323 --> 01:18:23,784
Okay, Bob. Hold it
about right there.

1194
01:18:25,119 --> 01:18:27,955
We're right over the tunnel.
Okay, we're all set down here.

1195
01:18:28,831 --> 01:18:30,332
MIKE: <i>Tell FitzRoyce
we're in position.</i>

1196
01:18:30,750 --> 01:18:32,918
FitzRoyce, you can go now.

1197
01:18:58,861 --> 01:19:01,197
They're testing the
lifeline to see if it's secure.

1198
01:19:24,094 --> 01:19:27,056
CALVIN: They're spreadin' some
chum. You know, fish oil and blood.

1199
01:19:27,681 --> 01:19:29,308
Then Jack's gonna make
some metallic sounds

1200
01:19:29,391 --> 01:19:31,936
to attract her right down
into that filtration pipe.

1201
01:19:34,313 --> 01:19:35,648
Start the pumps.

1202
01:19:35,731 --> 01:19:37,066
You got it.

1203
01:19:42,238 --> 01:19:44,240
(METAL CLANGING)

1204
01:19:44,406 --> 01:19:45,574
(METAL CLANGING)

1205
01:20:15,229 --> 01:20:18,232
(SHARK THEME PLAYING)

1206
01:21:07,114 --> 01:21:09,700
TECHNICIAN: It's in!
CALVIN: He's got it!

1207
01:21:11,660 --> 01:21:13,078
All right. It's locked.

1208
01:21:15,414 --> 01:21:16,916
It's safe, Brody.
Go for it.

1209
01:21:17,708 --> 01:21:18,876
Okay, let's go.

1210
01:22:11,011 --> 01:22:12,054
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

1211
01:22:47,089 --> 01:22:49,299
TECHNICIAN: <i>This is Control.
Is that tunnel patch in place?</i>

1212
01:22:49,800 --> 01:22:50,926
Easy.

1213
01:23:02,271 --> 01:23:04,273
Let me help you
with that, Dr. Morgan.

1214
01:23:04,398 --> 01:23:05,607
Got it!

1215
01:23:08,777 --> 01:23:10,279
Now weld the
son-of-a-bitch...

1216
01:23:12,948 --> 01:23:14,241
Kathryn,
what are you doin'?

1217
01:23:14,450 --> 01:23:15,826
I'm going down there.

1218
01:23:19,413 --> 01:23:20,539
You crazy?

1219
01:23:20,622 --> 01:23:22,916
He needs eyes in the
back of his head, Calvin.

1220
01:23:28,255 --> 01:23:29,798
Thanks, Fred.
All right.

1221
01:23:30,674 --> 01:23:32,301
Watch the tanks.

1222
01:23:33,135 --> 01:23:34,136
Okay.

1223
01:23:38,223 --> 01:23:39,641
Here are your fins.
Thanks.

1224
01:23:40,476 --> 01:23:41,935
Be careful down
there now.

1225
01:23:57,451 --> 01:23:59,661
(HINGES CREAKING)

1226
01:24:29,399 --> 01:24:31,068
(SIGHING)
You all right?

1227
01:24:32,611 --> 01:24:34,154
Where's Mr. FitzRoyce?

1228
01:24:34,238 --> 01:24:35,489
I have no idea.

1229
01:24:41,120 --> 01:24:42,454
MAN: What's goin' on?

1230
01:24:43,372 --> 01:24:44,873
Guv'nor!

1231
01:24:45,374 --> 01:24:46,792
Guv'nor!

1232
01:24:47,376 --> 01:24:48,669
Guv'nor!

1233
01:24:50,671 --> 01:24:52,172
There's no other way out?

1234
01:24:52,464 --> 01:24:54,216
You don't understand.
This is it!

1235
01:24:54,299 --> 01:24:55,509
Have you looked?

1236
01:24:56,385 --> 01:24:57,719
He didn't come up.

1237
01:24:58,971 --> 01:25:02,099
Guv'nor, you bloody bastard.
Answer me!

1238
01:25:08,939 --> 01:25:11,441
We'll suffocate the bitch.
Shut down the pumps.

1239
01:25:11,775 --> 01:25:12,985
Are you sure?

1240
01:25:13,402 --> 01:25:15,612
Why don't we blow it up?
Listen, nephew.

1241
01:25:16,238 --> 01:25:20,200
That's a $2.5 million turbine that's not
going up in smoke because of some damn fish!

1242
01:25:20,367 --> 01:25:22,161
Now shut the pumps down!

1243
01:25:24,746 --> 01:25:26,707
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING)

1244
01:25:26,915 --> 01:25:28,375
What's happened?

1245
01:25:29,418 --> 01:25:30,961
MAN: They've shut
the pumps off.

1246
01:25:31,920 --> 01:25:36,091
(SIGHING) That's all she needs.
The gates can't hold much longer.

1247
01:25:38,677 --> 01:25:42,264
(SOBBING) Philip, pull
the pin! Pull the pin, Philip.

1248
01:26:09,166 --> 01:26:11,543
(METALLIC CLANKING ON MONITOR)

1249
01:26:11,960 --> 01:26:13,879
(CLANKING)

1250
01:26:17,674 --> 01:26:19,968
(CLANKING CONTINUING)

1251
01:27:05,764 --> 01:27:07,140
WOMAN: Look at that!

1252
01:27:14,898 --> 01:27:16,400
WOMAN: Jesus!

1253
01:27:17,109 --> 01:27:18,694
FRED: Oh, my God!

1254
01:27:19,361 --> 01:27:20,862
We gotta warn 'em.
We gotta tell 'em!

1255
01:27:21,571 --> 01:27:22,572
Get 'em up!

1256
01:27:22,781 --> 01:27:24,950
It's coming back.
Get 'em up quick!

1257
01:27:25,033 --> 01:27:26,618
Come on! Hurry up!
Come on!

1258
01:27:26,785 --> 01:27:27,828
Get 'em up!

1259
01:27:42,175 --> 01:27:43,677
Come on, Mike.
Get out of there!

1260
01:27:50,934 --> 01:27:53,812
Come on, Mike!
CALVIN: <i>Get 'em up!</i>

1261
01:28:21,423 --> 01:28:22,466
(SHARK THEME PLAYING)

1262
01:28:22,549 --> 01:28:24,217
(MUFFLED) Come on!

1263
01:28:33,810 --> 01:28:34,853
(SQUEAKING)

1264
01:28:35,604 --> 01:28:37,105
(SQUEAKING)

1265
01:29:36,039 --> 01:29:37,249
(MUFFLED) Pull the door!

1266
01:30:02,983 --> 01:30:05,152
(GASPING)

1267
01:30:06,987 --> 01:30:08,572
How the hell
did it get loose?

1268
01:30:14,369 --> 01:30:15,704
Open the hatch!

1269
01:30:20,792 --> 01:30:23,044
FRED: Come on up,
Mike. I gotcha.

1270
01:30:29,384 --> 01:30:30,594
Are you all right?

1271
01:30:32,804 --> 01:30:34,139
Do we have pressure
in those tunnels yet?

1272
01:30:34,222 --> 01:30:37,225
Affirmative. Then open up the
bulkheads, get those people out of there.

1273
01:30:37,309 --> 01:30:38,393
Done.

1274
01:30:39,728 --> 01:30:41,897
Feel the air!
Can you feel the air?

1275
01:30:42,105 --> 01:30:44,065
The water's going down.
The water's going down!

1276
01:30:51,531 --> 01:30:53,283
Try to be calm.
Don't rush to the door.

1277
01:30:54,826 --> 01:30:56,578
We're saved!

1278
01:31:00,707 --> 01:31:02,250
(ALL CHEERING)

1279
01:31:20,268 --> 01:31:21,937
(SHARK THEME PLAYING)

1280
01:31:30,529 --> 01:31:32,656
(SCREAMING)

1281
01:32:10,527 --> 01:32:12,612
(MUFFLED YELLING)
(CRUNCHING)

1282
01:34:25,829 --> 01:34:27,497
Oh! We did it!

1283
01:34:27,872 --> 01:34:29,708
The others, Mike.
What about the others?

1284
01:34:30,458 --> 01:34:31,960
Calvin made it. Lisa.

1285
01:34:32,752 --> 01:34:36,089
Mike. Mike! The dolphins!

1286
01:34:37,590 --> 01:34:39,092
KAY: Cindy!

1287
01:34:39,300 --> 01:34:41,386
MIKE: Cindy!
KAY: Sandy!

1288
01:34:41,594 --> 01:34:43,304
Come on, girls! Cindy!
Cindy!

1289
01:34:45,014 --> 01:34:47,767
Oh, good girl. Sandy!

1290
01:34:48,226 --> 01:34:49,644
(SQUEAKING)

1291
01:34:49,686 --> 01:34:53,773
Sandy, come on, baby.
Sandy, where are you?

1292
01:34:54,649 --> 01:34:55,984
MIKE: Sandy!

1293
01:34:57,861 --> 01:34:59,154
I hope she made it.

1294
01:35:01,656 --> 01:35:03,241
Cindy, stay.
Sandy.

1295
01:35:04,159 --> 01:35:05,493
(SQUEAKING)

1296
01:35:06,995 --> 01:35:08,663
Sandy!

1297
01:35:09,372 --> 01:35:10,582
All right!

1298
01:35:23,344 --> 01:35:24,763
All right!